American's TV Interests¶

By Hosna Hooshyar

Defining the problem¶

Some tv series' first episodes or part of them are shown to a randomly selected group of audience before releasing the show. The audience then has to answer questions about what they saw. The aim is to anticipate the shows future, improve them if that is necessary and determine some key features, for example, the best day of the week for airing them. The networks rely on this process to save money, resources, and have the best outcome for the show.

This project is aiming to answer these questions:

  1. Analyzing the accuracy of these experiments. (How successful they are in predicting the shows popularity and success?).
  2. Which group of people is the best judges of the quality of tv shows? (Based on gender and education)
  3. Predicting people's opinions on the show
  4. Predicting if there will be a second season or not

Data-set¶

The source of the data is kaggle website: Link.

The data that is used in this project is collected by surveys. Each survey respondent was randomly shown one of 22 YouTube video previews for a television show debuting in the 2018/2019 season. All of the previews were distributed by the network to promote the show and they varied in length. After watching the video, respondents then provided their opinons on the shows with three features:

  1. Interest
  2. Uniqueness
  3. Relevance

The participants also answer questions about their lives including their gender, their education and etc. It is anticipated that the first limitation of the data is the participants' refusal to answer some of the questions. The other limitation that will affect the prediction models is the number of TV shows in this data which is only 22.

Cleaning, curation and exploring the data-set¶

Since our prediction model is as accurate as our data, the dataset needs to be studied carefully. There may be features that should be added, removed, or aggregated, the type of some of them may need to change (i.e. categorical to numerical) or there could be some missing data that must be dealt with. The first step is studying the features:

missing_data data-set shows the percentage of missing data in each column. Considering the questions of the survey, missing data can be categorized into two groups:

  1. The data participants refused to provide, for example separation_state column. This kind of missing value is called MNAR (Missing not at Random) and its related columns will be removed if a big percentage of their elements are missing. (Source)
  2. The data that although are missing, carry information. For example, around 63% of genres_reality column's values are missing which means 63% of people do not consider reality as their favorite genre.

The features of the list named missing belong to the first group of missing data.

In [37]:

Analyze¶

How accurate is the survey? (How successful is it in predicting the shows’ future?)¶

To answer this question the success features (IMDb rating, rotten tomatoes, Season 2) and the factors related to participants' opinions on tv shows (interest, uniqueness, relevance) will be compared. But first, the numerical factors should be put in the same range.

  1. IMDb rating = [1:10]
  2. Rotten tomatoes = [0:100]
  3. interest, uniqueness, and relevance = -2,-1,0,1,2

IMDb and Rotten tomatoes ratings will be converted to [-2:2] range.After that, the data-set will be named dataFrame_2

In [44]:
dataFrame_2 = dataFrame
dataFrame_2['IMDb rating'] = dataFrame_2['IMDb rating'].aggregate(
    lambda x: ((x-1)/(10-1))*(4)-2)
dataFrame_2['rotten tomatoes'] = dataFrame_2['rotten tomatoes'].aggregate(
    lambda x: ((x-0)/(100-0))*(4)-2)

In [51]:
for i in ['interest', 'uniqueness', 'relevance']:
    for j in ['IMDb rating', 'rotten tomatoes']:
        k = 0
        difference_percentage = ((dataFrame_success.groupby('title')[i].mean(
        ) - dataFrame_success.groupby('title')[j].mean())/dataFrame_success.groupby('title')[i].mean())*100
        print("Percentage difference between %s and %s is: \n %s" %
              (i, j, difference_percentage))
        for g in range(0, len(difference_percentage)-1):
            if np.abs(difference_percentage[g]) < 30:
                k += 1
            else:
                continue

In this experiment, 2939 people were shown a short video of one of the upcoming TV shows and they were asked to rate the show based on what they had seen. Using the above code, this rating was compared to IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes ratings (both of them achieved after one season of each show was aired). The first prediction feature in the survey is called Interest and out of 21 TV shows, only 6 of them managed to gain an IMDb rating with less than 30 percent difference with the Interest feature. Predicting viewers' level of interest based on critics' rating¶

The goal of this step is predicting the viewers' opinions based on the ratings that critics give the TV shows. As it was mentioned before, the numbers that were gained from the IMDb website indicate the viewers' ratings and numbers from the Rotten Tomatoes website show the critics' ratings. Basically, the goal is to predict the IMDb rating feature based on the rotten tomatoes feature. The problem is that the dataFrame data-set which was used until now, contains only 21 TV shows and since this amount of data is not enough for this purpose, a new data-set named renewalData will be analyzed. The new data frame was gained through searching IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes websites

def PolynomialRegression(degree=5, **kwargs):
    return make_pipeline(PolynomialFeatures(degree), LinearRegression(**kwargs))

def plot_svc_decision_function(model, ax=None, plot_support=True):
    if ax is None:
        ax = plt.gca()
    xlim = ax.get_xlim()
    ylim = ax.get_ylim()
    x = np.linspace(xlim[0], xlim[1], 30)
    y = np.linspace(ylim[0], ylim[1], 30)
    Y, X = np.meshgrid(y, x)
    xy = np.vstack([X.ravel(), Y.ravel()]).T
    P = model.decision_function(xy).reshape(X.shape)
    ax.contour(X, Y, 
               P, 
               colors='k',
               levels=[-1, 0, 1], alpha=0.5,
               linestyles=['--', '-', '--'])

    y_pred = svm_poly.predict(X_test)
    C_list_poly.append(i)
    Accuracy_list_poly.append(metrics.accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))

Conclusion¶

The initial data-set is a report on an experiment many TV channels do. They gather a randomly selected group of people and show them a short video of an upcoming TV show to know the weakness and strength of it and make some important decisions. The data-set is named dataFrame and it has 40 columns and 2939 rows. Each row belongs to a participant in one of the mentioned experiments.

First, the data was explored. Considering the questionnaire and the goal of the project, some columns and rows were removed and missing data and some values were replaced.

The first question that was answered was the level of accuracy. These experiments are designed to predict features related to the shows' future and one of these features is popularity. Therefore, the level of interest that the participants showed was compared to the score people gave the show after watching one season. Less than half of the shows managed to be as popular as the experiment suggested.

The second question's focus is also on the TV shows' popularity but this time gender and educational background of participants were key factors. It was found that the opinions of men and people with college and grad school degrees are closer to the reality of the whole season of a show.

The third question asked for a model to predict the people's opinions based on the critics'. people's and critics' opinions are represented by two features: IMDb ratings and Rotten Tomatoes ratings respectively. The obtained model is a linear regression model whose errors are high and not satisfactory. This can be caused because of two reasons:

  1. The data points not enough to build a prediction model based on them.
  2. It is not possible to predict one of these features based on the other, simply because regular viewers and critics have very different perspectives.

The last question was about the renewal of the shows and was answered by a Support Vector Machine classifier model. The type of kernels that were used are linear, RBF, and polynomial.

Since the original data-set consists of only 21 TV shows, the prediction models were built on new sets of data which give information of 79 and 158 TV shows. The error of the linear regression model increased with the number of data and then decreased when outliers were removed. As a result, we cannot say the first hypothesis is correct and the satisfactory prediction model can be obtained if the number of data points increases.

The accuracy of SVM models also increased when more data points were added to the data-set.

Unlike most data-sets, the data that was used in this project came from people's opinions, something that can change easily based on people's personalities, their age, or even the neighborhood they live in. So when dealing with this kind of data, the main challenge is considering all these aspects and how they can affect the results. For example, here we saw the male participants were better representants of the population. We could have come to a completely different conclusion If the TV shows were all in different genres that is more interesting to women. Although my knowledge of movies and TV series was very helpful for understanding the data and executing preprocessing.

There are some ways to improve this project. First of all, more data points will help both the analyze and prediction models. The other thing is considering the effect of each TV show's network on its renewl. There are many different networks out there and every one of them has a unique process for deciding which shows are benefitial enough to have another season.
